<!-- TYPES OF BATH CHIPS WE FIX -->
<section class="py-16 sm:py-20 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 sm:px-8">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-primary tracking-tighter mb-4">Types of Bath Chips We Fix</h2>
        <p class="text-secondary max-w-3xl mb-10">Not sure what type of damage you're looking at? Here are the most common bath chips we see and repair across Sydney homes.</p>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4 gap-6">
            <div class="bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl p-6 reveal">
                <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-3xl text-error mb-3 block" aria-hidden="true">brightness_1</span>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-primary mb-2">Surface Chips</h3>
                <p class="text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed">Small dings and nicks from dropped bottles, razors, or taps banging against the bath. The top coating is chipped but the underlying material is intact. These are the most common and easiest to repair &mdash; usually just a few millimetres across.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl p-6 reveal">
                <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-3xl text-error mb-3 block" aria-hidden="true">crater</span>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-primary mb-2">Deep Chips</h3>
                <p class="text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed">Heavier impacts that go right through the coating to the substrate underneath &mdash; you can see bare metal on steel/cast iron baths, or the fibreglass backing on acrylic baths. These need filling and building up in layers before coating.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl p-6 reveal">
                <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-3xl text-error mb-3 block" aria-hidden="true">vertical_split</span>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-primary mb-2">Hairline Cracks</h3>
                <p class="text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed">Fine cracks in the bath surface, often caused by thermal stress or minor flex in acrylic baths. They may look small but they let water through to the substrate below. We stabilise, fill, and seal these to stop them spreading.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl p-6 reveal">
                <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-3xl text-error mb-3 block" aria-hidden="true">rounded_corner</span>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-primary mb-2">Edge &amp; Rim Damage</h3>
                <p class="text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed">Chips along the top edge or rim of the bath, typically from items being placed on the ledge or from wear over many years. Rim chips are highly visible and often the first thing people notice. We rebuild the profile and finish to match.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- WHY YOU SHOULDN'T LEAVE IT -->
<section class="py-16 sm:py-20 bg-surface-container-low">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 sm:px-8">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-primary tracking-tighter mb-4">Why You Shouldn't Leave It</h2>
        <p class="text-secondary max-w-3xl mb-10">A bath chip might seem like a minor cosmetic issue, but leaving it untreated can lead to bigger and more expensive problems.</p>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 max-w-4xl">
            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-8 border-l-4 border-error reveal">
                <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-2xl text-error mb-3 block" aria-hidden="true">iron</span>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-primary mb-2">Rust Spreads</h3>
                <p class="text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed">On steel and cast iron baths, a chip exposes the bare metal underneath. Once moisture gets in, rust begins forming and spreads <em>under</em> the surrounding enamel &mdash; lifting and bubbling the coating outward from the original chip. What starts as a small spot can become a large rusted area.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-8 border-l-4 border-error reveal">
                <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-2xl text-error mb-3 block" aria-hidden="true">water_damage</span>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-primary mb-2">Water Damage</h3>
                <p class="text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed">On acrylic baths, chips and cracks can allow water to seep behind the bath shell and into the supporting structure. Over time this can weaken the bath base, damage the floor underneath, and create conditions for mould growth in hidden cavities.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-8 border-l-4 border-error reveal">
                <span class="material-symbols-outlined text-2xl text-error mb-3 block" aria-hidden="true">trending_up</span>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-primary mb-2">Gets Worse</h3>
                <p class="text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed">Small chips become bigger over time. The rough edge catches on cloths and sponges, gradually widening the damage. Hairline cracks extend further with each hot-cold cycle. Fixing a small chip now is far simpler and cheaper than dealing with widespread damage later.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- HOW WE FIX IT -->
<section class="py-16 sm:py-20 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 sm:px-8">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-primary tracking-tighter mb-4">How We Fix a Chipped Bath</h2>
        <p class="text-secondary max-w-3xl mb-10">Our chip repair process restores the damaged area to a smooth, sealed, colour-matched finish. This is for localised chip damage &mdash; if your entire bath surface is worn, stained, or peeling, see our <a href="<?php echo esc_url( home_url( '/services/bath-resurfacing-sydney/' ) ); ?>" class="text-primary underline font-medium hover:text-primary-container">full bath resurfacing service</a>.</p>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
            <div class="bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl p-6 reveal">
                <div class="w-12 h-12 rounded-full bg-primary text-white flex items-center justify-center font-bold mb-4">1</div>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-primary text-sm mb-2">Clean &amp; Prep the Area</h3>
                <p class="text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">We thoroughly clean the chipped area and surrounding surface, removing any dirt, soap residue, or loose material. On steel/cast iron baths, any rust is carefully treated and removed back to clean metal before we proceed.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl p-6 reveal">
                <div class="w-12 h-12 rounded-full bg-primary text-white flex items-center justify-center font-bold mb-4">2</div>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-primary text-sm mb-2">Fill with Professional Filler</h3>
                <p class="text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">We apply a professional two-part epoxy filler specifically matched to your bath type. Enamel baths and acrylic baths require different filler formulations &mdash; using the right one ensures proper adhesion and a long-lasting bond.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl p-6 reveal">
                <div class="w-12 h-12 rounded-full bg-primary text-white flex items-center justify-center font-bold mb-4">3</div>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-primary text-sm mb-2">Build Up &amp; Shape</h3>
                <p class="text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">For deeper chips, we build up the filler in thin layers to match the original profile of the bath surface. Each layer is allowed to set before the next is applied. This ensures a solid, void-free repair that won't sink or shrink over time.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl p-6 reveal">
                <div class="w-12 h-12 rounded-full bg-primary text-white flex items-center justify-center font-bold mb-4">4</div>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-primary text-sm mb-2">Sand Smooth &amp; Blend</h3>
                <p class="text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">Once cured, the filler is sanded through progressively finer grades until it's perfectly smooth and level with the surrounding bath surface. The edges are feathered and blended so there's no visible step or ridge.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface-container-low rounded-xl p-6 reveal">
                <div class="w-12 h-12 rounded-full bg-primary text-white flex items-center justify-center font-bold mb-4">5</div>
                <h3 class="font-bold text-primary text-sm mb-2">Colour-Match &amp; Seal</h3>
                <p class="text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">A colour-matched coating is carefully applied over the repair to blend it into the existing bath finish. This final layer seals the repair completely, making it waterproof and giving it the same sheen as the rest of the bath surface.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

